    <h2>Common questions from White Lake clients</h2>
    <details class="faq-item"><summary>I have a dock and a boat hoist — are those covered under my homeowners policy?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>It depends on how the policy is written. Docks, hoists, and other waterfront structures usually fall under Coverage B (Other Structures), which defaults to 10% of your dwelling limit. On a $500K home that's only $50K — often not enough for a serious dock setup. We size Coverage B specifically to what you actually have on the water.</p></div></details>
    <details class="faq-item"><summary>Should I insure my boat on my homeowners policy or with a standalone marine policy?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>Almost always a standalone marine policy. The boat rider on a homeowners policy usually has very low liability limits and treats the hull as personal property (depreciated, not replacement cost). A standalone marine policy gives you proper hull coverage, agreed value, real liability limits (often $500K+), uninsured boater coverage, and on-water towing. We can usually quote a marine policy in 5 minutes.</p></div></details>
    <details class="faq-item"><summary>Do I need flood insurance on a lake home?</summary><div class="faq-body"><p>Not always, but it's worth checking. Some White Lake parcels sit in or near a flood zone, and standard homeowners policies exclude flood. We can pull a flood quote alongside your home quote and walk you through whether the cost is worth it for your specific property.</p></div></details>

